# Git commit conventions

Use **Conventional Commits** so history is clear and tools (GitHub, changelogs) work well.

## Format

```
type(scope?): subject

body? (optional)
footer? (optional)
```

- **type(scope?):** required. Scope is optional (e.g. area like `auth`, `ui`, `api`).
- **subject:** required, short imperative summary.
- **body:** optional, wrap at 72 characters.
- **footer:** optional (e.g. `BREAKING CHANGE:`, `Refs #123`).

## Allowed types

- `feat` – new feature
- `fix` – bug fix
- `docs` – documentation only
- `style` – formatting, no code change (e.g. whitespace, semicolons)
- `refactor` – code change that is not a fix or feature
- `test` – adding or updating tests
- `chore` – build, tooling, deps, no app logic change

## Rules

- **Subject:** imperative, lowercase start, no period at end. Keep to ~50 characters when possible; max ~72.
- **Body:** explain what and why, not how. Wrap lines at 72 characters.
- **Scope:** use when it helps (e.g. `feat(auth): add login`, `fix(ui): header alignment`).

## Examples

- `feat(auth): add JWT login and register`
- `fix(review): show score when feedback is empty`
- `docs: update README run instructions`
- `style: align login and signup cards`
- `chore(deps): bump next to 14.2.3`

When writing or suggesting commit messages, follow this format.
